N2  - Background and Aims: In Peru, there is an average delay of 16 hours between the onset of fever and the presentation to the Emergency Room (ER) for pediatric cancer patients. This delay hinders the timely administration of antibiotics and increases the risk of mortality due to sepsis. This regional collaborative study explores the prehospital experience of caregivers who transported their pediatric oncology patients to the ER due to febrile neutropenia (FN). Methods: 18 caregivers of pediatric oncology patients who had experienced at least one FN episode treated in Peruvian public hospitals were interviewed. The transcribed interviews were analyzed using an inductive thematic approach with Dedoose software as part of a broader study on parental self-efficacy. The analysis identified categories that characterize the prehospital experience. Results: Based on the caregivers' narratives, the identified categories were organized into a timeline encompassing experiences (A) before transport, (B) during transport, and (C) before receiving ER care. A total of 9 categories were identified in the prehospital experience: (1) Key knowledge, (2) Access to information, (3) Anticipation/preparation, (4) Recognition of the need for emergency care, (5) Patient attitudes toward the emergency, (6) Transportation time to the ER, (7) Coping resources, and (8) Perception of care. A cross-cutting category prevalent throughout the entire timeline was (9) Parental self-recognition, as caregivers frequently expressed validation of their experiences and acquired knowledge Conclusions: The identified categories highlight personal variables (knowledge, behaviors, and self-perceptions) and psychosocial factors influencing timely ER arrival. These findings could inform the development of a screening tool to identify cases with greater or lesser barriers to accessing emergency care.
