N2  - Objective: Diabetes mellitus and hyperglycemia have been described as risk factors for adverse outcome in COVID-19. The aim of this study was to evaluate the association between admission blood glucose and adverse outcomes in non-critical hospitalized patients with COVID-19 in a multidisciplinary service of a Peruvian hospital. Methods: This is a retrospective cohort-type observational study, which included all patients hospitalized for COVID-19 during the months of April to June 2020, followed until discharge or death, in a COVID-19 medical specialities ward. We classified patients according to history of DM and blood glucose levels at admission. The primary endpoint was composite outcome (death, septic shock, mechanical ventilation, or transfer to a critical care unit) related to COVID-19. Results: We evaluated 169 patients mean age was 61 years old, and 64.5% were male. 71% had at least one comorbidity, of which hypertension (34%), obesity (30%) and DM (26%) were the most frequent. About symptoms, dyspnea, cough and fever were the most frequent. 70% presented tomographic severity. mean admission blood glucose was 126.5 ± 48 mg / dL, 1 in 2 had glycemia greater than 140 mg / dL. Cohort mortality rate was 9.7 per 100 person-week. Mortality rate was 9.7 deaths per 100 person-weeks, with a frequency of 21.3%. There was no significant difference between hyperglycemia and mortality, nor in composite outcome. Hyperglycemic group had a longer hospital stay than normoglycemic one (19 days vs 13 days, p < 0.01). In subanalysis with multivariate logistic regression for composite outcome among diabetic patients, admission blood glucose > 180mg / dL had 6.42 (1.07-38.6) greater risk for adverse composite outcome than patients with blood glucose ≤ 180mg / dL, this adjusted to age and admission clinical severity. Discussion/Conclusion: Hyperglycemia on admission is a factor associated with adverse outcomes in diabetic patients and is correlated with hospital stay among survivors.
