N2  - Background: Introduction It is important to reconstruct the skull for the recovery of a patient's quality of life. There are different methods and materials available for cranioplasty. Points to be considered are the resistance to stress of the material, good adaptation to the contour of the cranial defect, surgical operating time, risk of infection and aesthetic results. Clinical case A fifty three year old male patient presented with a severe cranial defect after right fronto orbito temporal and orbito zygomatic partial resection for mucormycosis. He had undergone three surgical procedures of resection. He had also received specific antimycotic treatment with good response but showed severe craniofacial sequelae. Objectives: To demonstrate the importance of the incorporation of prototyping in the personalization of cranial titanium implants. Methods: Material and methods A 1.5 mm gauge titanium mesh, pre shaped with a 3D printing, was used for reconstruction of a defect on the right temporo orbital region. Findings: Results A cranioplasty was performed with good aesthetic and functional results. The pre shaped titanium mesh was well adapted to the cranial defect Conclusion: The use of a customized preshaped titanium mesh for the reconstruction of selected cranial defects offers good aesthetic results at the same time reducing operating time and cost with a very low risk of infection. Bibliographic references • Journal of Craniofacial Surgery: March 2008 – Volume 19 – Issue 2- p 490-495. • Andrabi, S.M., Sarmast, A.H., Kirmani, A.R., & Bhat, A.R. (2017). Cranioplasty: Indications, Procedures, and outcome- an institutional experience.
