N2  - Background: Red blood cell distribution width (RDW) has emerged as a potential prognostic factor in diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) and a reliable and easy-to-use predictive tool. Methods: We performed a retrospective study on consecutive patients with a de novo diagnosis of DLBCL treated at our institution between 2010 and 2012. All patients included were treated with chemotherapy or chemoinmunotherapy with a curative intent. RDW > 14.6% was our cut-off. We fitted logistic regression models and Cox proportional-hazard regression models. Results: 121 patients with de novo DLBCL were included. Eighty patients (66%) had age ≥60 years, 54 patients (45%) were men, 41 patients (34%) had ECOG ≥2, 70 patients (58%) had increased LDH levels, 69 patients (57%) had > 1 extranodal site, 49 patients (41%) had stage III/IV disease, and 72 patients (60%) had B symptoms. Patients with high RDW (45 patients, 39%) were more likely to have ECOG ≥2 (53% vs. 21%; p < 0.001), elevated LDH levels (77% vs. 46%, p = 0.001), stage III/IV (53% vs. 34%; p = 0.04) and presence of B symptoms (54% vs. 18%; p < 0.001). Patients with high RDW also had higher IPI score (59% vs. 24%; p < 0.001) and also higher NCCN-IPI scores (53% vs. 21%, p < 0.001). They were less likely to achieve CR to therapy (48% vs. 83%; p < 0.001). In the multivariate logistic regression analyses, high RDW was a strong predictor of not achieving CR (OR 0.25, 95% CI 0.10-0.66; p = 0.005). With a median follow-up time of 5.6 years, the 5-year OS rate for patients with high RDW was 51% (95% CI 36-65%) versus 79% (95% CI 68- 87%) in patients with normal RDW (p = 0.001). In the univariate Cox regression analysis, high RDW was associated with HR 2.63 (95% CI 1.41-4.89; p = 0.002). In the multivariate Cox regression analyses, high RDW was a stronger predictor of poor survival (HR 1.92, 95% CI 0.99-3.73; p = 0.05) than the IPI score (HR 1.34, 95% CI 0.58-3.11; p = 0.49) and the NCCN-IPI score (HR 2.21, 95% CI 0.87-5.59; p = 0.09). Conclusions: High RDW appears to be an adverse predictor of response and survival in patients with de novo DLBCL treated with R-CHOP, independent of the IPI and NCCN-IPI scores.
