N2  - Rationale: Predictive scoring systems are measures of disease severity commonly used in assessing patient status in intensive care units (ICUs). Thus far, scoring systems have primarily focused on cross-sectional indicators from a single hospital day. The objective of this study was to compare the accuracy of various predictors of 90-day mortality: traditional scoring systems, an individual combination score derived from them, and a novel score based on longitudinal measurements of acute physiologic variables. Methods: This study was a secondary analysis of data collected during the prospective INTENSIVOS Cohort Study from five Peruvian ICU units of mechanically-ventilated patients ≥18 years old. Demographic and baseline clinical information was collected upon the participant's admission to the ICU. Severity scores, including APACHE II, APACHE III, SOFA, and SAPS II were calculated. Daily information, including laboratory tests, clinical management, ventilation management, and medication use was collected each day for the first 28 days or until death or discharge from the ICU. Vital status was assessed at 15, 30, 45, 60, and 90 days after initiation of mechanical ventilation. Results: During the study, 1657 participants met criteria of admission. Ages ranged from 18-101 years old, with a mean of 60.1. Mean length of stay in the ICU was 16.8 days. Forty-nine percent of participants (810) died within 90 days of admission. The overall c-statistics for the prediction of 90-day mortality from traditional scoring systems include: APACHE II - 0.66, APACHE III - 0.64, SAPS II - 0.64, and SOFA - 0.62. The overall c-statistic for composite score was 0.65. Prediction accuracy increased (c=0.84) when utilizing trajectories established from longitudinal measurements while in the ICU. Figure 1 displays Receiver Operator Curves (ROC) for each method above. Conclusions: Longitudinal data improved upon the accuracy of cross-sectional baseline scores when predicting 30-, 60-, and 90- day morality. Consideration should be given to include a longitudinal component into mortality predictive scoring systems. (Figure presented) .
