N2  - Background: Although Ki-67 is important in sub classifying luminal breast cancers, many reports from Latin American Countries does not include the evaluation of this marker in the immunohistochemistry panel. Our aim was to describe expression of ER, PR, HER2 and the frequency of breast cancer phenotypes identified for a panel of immunohistochemistry biomarkers, including Ki-67, in a cohort of Latin American women. Methods: We enrolled in a prospective study 580 patients from 4 centers in Lima (Peru) and one in Montevideo (Uruguay). Breast cancer phenotypes were classified according the expressions of ER, PR, HER2 and Ki-67. In addition, SISH analysis was used in cases with HER2 equivocal status (HER2 2+). Results: The ER was positive in 65% (n = 377) of cases, the PR in 50% (n = 203), 79.1% (n = 459) were HER2 negative, 19.8% (n = 115) were HER2 positive and 1% (n = 6) were equivocal. In regard to Ki-67 expression, 55.3% (n = 321) had an expression 14% and 44.7% (n = 259) had an expression > 14%. Subtypes were luminal A, 31.9% (n = 183); luminal B, 35% (n = 201); HER2, 12.1% (n = 70) and triple negative, 20.9% (n = 120). When Ki-67 is not included in the panel, frequency of luminal A is 41.1% and luminal B is 25.8%. Conclusions: Luminal B tumors were most frequent while frequency of luminal A tumors are overestimated if Ki-67 is not evaluated. Frequency of triple negative and HER2 tumors were similar to described previously for Latin American population.
