N2  - Background: To determine the factors associated with average length of total androgen blockade (TAB) response and overall survival (OS) in newly diagnosed patients with metastatic prostate cancer (MCP) in a general hospital in Peru. Methods: This is an observational, retrospective and cross-sectional study. Fifty-four patients newly diagnosed with MCP who were treated at the Central Military Hospital during the period of January 2000 through December 2007 were reviewed. Length of TAB was defined as use of LHRH analog or orchiectomy + / - antiandrogen ,Overall survival was defined as the number of months of survival from diagnosis to death. Results: The median age at diagnosis was 74 years (range: 51-88 years). Following diagnosis, 21 patients (39%) received medical TAB and 44 (61%)underwent orchiectomy. Gleason scores of ≤6, 7 and ≥8 were seen in 26 (48%), 15 (28%) and 13 patients (24%), respectively, and 18 (33%), 19 (35%) and 17 patients (31%) had a total PSA of <50, 50-100 and >100 ng/ml, respectively. The median duration of response to TAB was 46 months (range: 9-85 months) and the median OS was 52 months (range: 12-99 months). According to Gleason scores of ≤6, 7, ≥8, response duration to TAB was 53, 45 and 23 months, respectively (Log-rank p<0.05). According to total PSA value <50, 50-100 and >100 ng/ml, the median duration of response to TAB was 56, 33 and 31 months, respectively (p<0.05). According to Gleason scores of ≤6, 7, ≥8, the median OS was 61, 58 and 28 months, respectively (p<0.05), and according to total PSA value <50, 50-100 and >100 ng/ml, the median OS was 63,38 and 36 months respectively (p<0.05). Conclusions: The Gleason score and the total PSA value at diagnosis were factors associated with duration of response to TAB and OS in Peruvian patients newly diagnosed with MPC. Survival data is similar to asiatic casuistry.
